<h2><%= @tool['title'] %> Parameters</h2>

<a name="input"></a>
<h3>Input Format</h3> 
<div class="row">
Prepare the target shifts in SHIFTX file format (example follows) <br><br>

<pre> NUM RES HA     H      N        CA      CB      C
  --- --- ------ ------ -------- ------- ------- --------
    1   M 4.3215 8.3001 120.3496 54.8524 32.2672 172.9036
    2   A 4.0305 7.9373 120.8557 49.2961 21.7604 171.6772
    3   V 4.1755 9.5017 123.7657 61.8993 34.5571 173.2111
    4   E 3.4846 8.4802 127.4171 57.4460 28.7679 178.0909
    5   E 4.3270 8.8690 131.7955 55.1248 29.1562 173.7310
    6   V 0.00   8.0282 125.2640 61.9025 32.3034 175.7654
    7   I 4.0634 8.6714 131.1148 60.8345 37.5008 175.3402
    8   E 4.8652 8.6917 127.9383 55.1060 29.8975 175.5015</pre>

<table>
<tr><td width ="120" valign="top" align="right">*</td><td width = "300">There have to be two header lines, followed by the lines describing the
    chemical shift values. If a chemical shift value is not available, please 
    set the value to 0.00, as it is done for the HA shift of residue number 6 
    in the example.</td></tr>
<tr><td align="right" valign="top">*</td><td>The second section of the standard SHIFTX file (describing shift for 
    various side chain hydrogens) does not have to be included.</td></tr>

<tr><td valign="top" align="left">TAKE CARE:</td><td> Only three shift values in each line are used for the alignment 
             calculation. If more than three shift values are available, the 
             first three available values are selected acoording to the 
             following atom ranking: CA(1)-CB(2)-C(3)-N(4)-HA(5)-H(6).
             If you want to make sure that a certain set of shifts is used for
             the alignment caculation, set the others to 0.00. (for example
             if you want to calculate the alignments based on HA, H and CA 
             shifts, then you have to set CB, C and N to 0.00.)</td></tr>
<tr height="50"><td></td><td></td></tr>
</div></table>
